Here is the translation of the conversation into simple English.

**Note:** The original text contains "Singlish" (Singaporean English) and Chinese dialect words (like Hokkien and Cantonese). The translation below captures the meaning and casual tone while removing the specific local slang for clarity.

***

**Alice:**
Haha.
Yeah, me too.
I really like playing, but I never gamble.
:)

**Bob:**
Or... I never gamble on Big Two either.
Except for that one time a few weeks ago.

**Alice:**
Oh, did you lose money a few weeks ago?

**Bob:**
I went to a friend’s house.
He wanted to play Big Two.
I said, "Okay, let’s play."
He said, "One cent per card..." (because he’s very good at the game).
I thought, "Okay, fine." Besides, I would only lose at most $10.

**Alice:**
Oh, you lost.
:)
Haha. It’s okay, you’ll get over it.
It’s actually fine. But if you have to gamble, I wouldn’t be able to enjoy the game fully.

**Bob:**
But it’s not good to be so stubborn about it.
Yeah, if you have to gamble, it’s very stressful.
By the way, do you have the software/program for it?

**Alice:**
What program?
No, I don’t.
You need to download it or something.
:)

**Bob:**
Well, if you want to play online, you obviously need a program to play.
My current client doesn’t support file transfers yet. Maybe I can send it to you via FTP or HTTP... wait a moment.

**Alice:**
Okay.
:)
No problem.
Haha. [end of text]


